Within an instance of interpersonal combat, "to the death" expresses an agreement-- or suggestion-- that victory will be decided by the death of one the contendors. (Or in the case of a massive fight, victory will be decided by the death of all but one contendor.)

For example, in tournament sword-fighting, or bar-room brawling, and other forms of battle, most contendors do not wish to kill or be killed. Victory is decided by physical defeat of ones enemy, either by outfighting them by some criteria, causing them to become unconscious, forcing them into a state of submission, or by a contendor scoring more "points" for his performance or skills than his opponent, as judged by some third party.

In a "to the death" contest, only the winner will emerge alive. There is no criterion for victory other than a death-- a knockout, pin, tap-out submission, out-maneuvering, will not suffice for victory and does not signal the end of the contest.